\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Stablecoins and Fixed Income Assets
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since their inception, crypto currencies aim to create an alternative financial
 system comparable to fiat financial system.
 In fiat system, money or credits exist in a few different forms: actual
 currency in circulation and fixed income assets such as time deposits and
 money market funds, which are the foundation for rest of the financial
 market to build on.
 The crypto market is at primitive stage as it lacks coins or tokens comparable
 to fiat money due to their huge price volatility and thus there is no establish
ed fixed income assets either.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A Stable token, also known as stablecoin, is a crypto-token that keeps stable
 market value against a specific index, most noticeably US Dollar.
 There has been a few attempts to create stable tokens: Tether claims to
 have 1:1 USD collateral in its centralized bank accounts; Basecoin tries
 to control money supply by playing an algorithmic version of central bank;
 MakerDAO uses decentralized over-collateralization to maintain confidence
 of its Dai stablecoin.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Most stable token designs to date share a common problem: their holders
 bear variable levels of counter-party risks, but there is little incentive
 or even additional cost to hold these tokens.
 We believe a crypto-token with low price volatility and stable income is
 a superior safe haven asset and is essential for a more robust crypto market.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Risk Segmentation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In fiat market, risk segmentation exists in every level of market.
 At asset class level, risk averse investors choose fixed income products
 while risk seeking investors choose equity or commodity.
 Within fixed income market, conservative investors choose safe haven assets
 such as government bonds while aggressive players choose high yield bonds,
 or otherwise known as junk bonds.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Although most of crypto assets are considered highly speculative, there
 still exist different segments of risk appetites.
 The existence of margin trading in exchanges like BitFinex and Huobi Pro
 demonstrates the need of leverage from aggressive crypto investors.
 Similarly, safe haven assets providing low volatility and stable income
 will be appealing to institutional players, short-term pessimistic investors
 and ICO project teams.
 However, to our best knowledge, there is no viable product at the moment.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The price volatility cannot be eliminated, but can be transferred.
 Through a structured contract, a risk-seeking user can get exposed to higher
 leverage with limited assets, while a risk-averse user can avoid unwanted
 price fluctuations by entering the other side of the contract.
 The financial market has created many products satisfying different risk
 segments, some of which can be very practical for crypto market participants.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Leveraged Funds
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Leverage is the strategy of using borrowed capital to increase the potential
 return of an investment.
 Retail investors have less access to leverage methods such as margin loans
 and financial derivatives, which promoted the creation of leveraged fund
 products.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A interesting class of leveraged funds is the dual-purpose funds, also known
 as primes and scores, which are mutual funds that are split into two classes
 of shares by design: low risk shares and high risk shares.
 They were designed to provide investors with the opportunity of repackaging
 their investment incomes and capital flow in accordance with their preferences.
 Dual-purpose funds first appeared in U.S.
 in 1965, but faded out in early 1990s due to a change in the tax code that
 resulted in double taxation.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DM2018"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The dual-purpose fund was introduced in China in 2010 and it quickly became
 the most popular leveraged product there, reaching market size of 500 billion
 CNY (80 Billion USD) at its peak.
 A Chinese dual-purpose fund usually takes an open-end index-tracking fund
 as underlying and has two classes of shares: the low risk A shares behave
 like a perpetual bond with periodical coupon payments, and the high risk
 B shares are essentially a closed-end fund magnifying the exposure of the
 underlying index.
 A set of upward and downward reset clauses is imposed to reduce the risk
 of both shares.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DM2018"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are attracted by Chinese dual-purpose fund for three reasons: (i) both
 the income and leveraged shares answer unfulfilled demands of cryptocurrency
 users; (ii) the market mechanism, pricing formula and arbitrage method
 are proven working in real market; and (iii) the structure can be efficiently
 implemented by Smart Contracts.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Smart Contract
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Product Design
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Overview
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
DUO 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
a dual-class token structure that, combined with smart contract governed
 rules and market arbitrage mechanism, provides principal-guaranteed fixed
 incomes and leveraged capital gains for holders of each class.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Class A Token
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
also known as the Income Token, continuously accumulates interests based
 on its original net value at last Reset event.
 It will receive token payments at each Reset event.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Class B Token
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
also known as the Leverage Token, entitles leveraged participation of the
 underlying digital assets.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Custodian smart contract performs multiple tasks that facilitate key
 mechanism of the system, including: creation and redemption of DUO tokens,
 safekeeping the underlying digital assets (e.g.
 ETH), calculation of tokens' net values, and execution of Reset events.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Creation and Redemption
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Creation-and-Redemption"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Creation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Dual-class tokens can be created by depositing underlying tokens to the
 Custodian contract.
 Upon receiving underlying tokens, the Custodian contract will return to
 the sender certain amount of Class A and Class B tokens.
 Such amount 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{A}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{B}$
\end_inset

 can be calculated by:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{array}{cc}
C_{B}= & \frac{M_{C}\cdot P_{0}\cdot\left(1-c\right)}{1+\alpha}\\
C_{A}= & C_{B}\cdot\alpha
\end{array}\label{eq:creation}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where, 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{C}$
\end_inset

 is the amount of underlying tokens sent to the Custodian contract,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 is the processing fee of the smart contract,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is a positive number for determine the ratio of A and B
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $P_{0}$
\end_inset

 is the recorded price of underlying token in USD at last Reset event.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The deposited underlying tokens are kept by the Custodian contract, as collatera
l of the Class A and Class B tokens issued by the contract.
 Any user or member of the public can verify the collateral and tokens issued
 through third party applications such as 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "Etherscan.io"
target "etherscan.io"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Redemption
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Holders of Class A and Class B tokens can withdraw deposited underlying
 tokens at any time by performing a redemption.
 To do this, the user will send certain amount of Class A and Class B tokens
 to the Custodian contract.
 The contract will deduct Class A and Class B tokens, and return return
 to the sender certain amount of underlying tokens.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The amount 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{A}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{B}$
\end_inset

 deducted by the contract is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
R & =\min\left\{ \frac{M_{A}}{\alpha},M_{B}\right\} \\
R_{A} & =R\cdot\alpha\\
R_{B} & =R
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where, 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{A}$
\end_inset

 is the amount of Class A sent to the Custodian contract,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $M_{B}$
\end_inset

 is the amount of Class B sent to the Custodian contract.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The amount 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{R}$
\end_inset

 returned by the contract is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
M_{R}=\frac{R\cdot\left(1-c\right)\cdot\left(1+\alpha\right)}{P_{0}}\label{eq:redemption}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Net Value
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The net value of tokens are calculated based on the coupon rate, the elapsed
 time from last Reset event, and the latest underlying token price in USD
 fed to the system.
 In particular:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
V_{A}^{t} & =1+r\cdot t\\
V_{B}^{t} & =\left(1+\alpha\right)\cdot\frac{P_{t}}{P_{0}}-\alpha\cdot V_{A}^{t}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where, 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is the daily coupon rate,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 is the number of days from last Reset event,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $P_{t}$
\end_inset

 is the current price of underlying token in USD.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Quantity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Below holds in the system at all time
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Q_{A}^{t}=Q_{B}^{t}\cdot\alpha
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where, 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{A}^{t}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{B}^{t}$
\end_inset

 are the total amount of Class A and Class B tokens.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Implied Leverage Ratio
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
L_{B}^{t} & =\frac{P_{t}}{P_{0}}\cdot\frac{\left(1+\alpha\right)}{V_{B}^{t}}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that at inception, above simply reduces to 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L_{B}^{0}=1+\alpha
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Resets
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Simply put, the holders of Class B tokens borrow capital from the holders
 of Class A tokens and invest in a volatile asset (i.e.
 ETH), which leads the Class B token to possess a continuum of leverage
 ratios.
 To reduce risk of both classes, a set of upward and downward reset clauses
 is imposed.
 Resets preserves total value in the system.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Contingent Upward 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When underlying token price rises, the Class B token's leverage ratio reduces.
 An Upward Reset is triggered when the Net Value of Class B token reaches
 upper limit
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}_{B}$
\end_inset

.
 The reset will restore the leverage ratio to 
\begin_inset Formula $1+\alpha$
\end_inset

, and the Net Value of both classes to 1 USD.
 By increasing Class B's leverage ratio, the structure retains attraction
 to leverage-seeking users.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Upon Upward Reset, both classes' holders will receive certain amount of
 ETH from the Custodian contract.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The underlying token amount 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{A}$
\end_inset

 for each Class A token and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{B}$
\end_inset

 for each Class B token:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
U_{A} & =\frac{\left(V_{A}^{t-}-1\right)}{P_{t}}\\
U_{B} & =\frac{\left(V_{B}^{t-}-1\right)}{P_{t}}\\
V_{A}^{t+} & =V_{A}^{0}=1\\
V_{B}^{t+} & =V_{B}^{0}=1\\
Q_{B}^{t+} & =Q_{B}^{t-}\\
Q_{A}^{t+} & =Q_{A}^{t-}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Total value in the system is unchanged after reset:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
 & U_{A}\cdot P_{t}\cdot Q_{A}^{t-}+U_{B}\cdot P_{t}\cdot Q_{B}^{t-}+Q_{A}^{t+}\cdot V_{A}^{t+}+Q_{B}^{t+}\cdot V_{B}^{t+}\\
= & \left(V_{A}^{t-}-1\right)\cdot Q_{A}^{t-}+\left(V_{B}^{t-}-1\right)\cdot Q_{B}^{t-}+Q_{A}^{t-}\cdot1+Q_{B}^{t-}\cdot1\\
= & V_{A}^{t-}\cdot Q_{A}^{t-}+V_{B}^{t-}\cdot Q_{B}^{t-}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Contingent Downward
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When underlying token price falls, the Class B token's leverage ratio increases.
 A Downward Reset is triggered when the Net Value of Class B token reaches
 lower limit 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

.
 Similar to an Upward Reset, a Downward Reset restores the leverage ratio
 and Net Value of both classes.
 By reducing leverage ratio and restoring Net Value, the structure strengthens
 principal protection to Class A holders.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Class A holder will receive certain amount of underlying token from the
 Custodian contract.
 Additionally, a Downward Reset will reduce the total supply of Class A
 and Class B tokens by roughly 
\begin_inset Formula $1-h$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The underlying token amount 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{A}$
\end_inset

 of each Class A token is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
D_{A} & =\frac{\left(V_{A}^{t-}-V_{B}^{t-}\right)}{P_{t}}\\
Q_{B}^{t+} & =Q_{B}^{t-}\cdot V_{B}^{t-}\\
Q_{A}^{t+} & =Q_{B}^{t+}\cdot\alpha\\
V_{A}^{t+} & =V_{A}^{0}=1\\
V_{B}^{t+} & =V_{B}^{0}=1
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Total value in the system is unchanged after reset:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
 & D_{A}\cdot P_{t}\cdot Q_{A}^{t-}+Q_{A}^{t+}\cdot V_{A}^{t+}+Q_{B}^{t+}\cdot V_{B}^{t+}\\
= & \left(V_{A}^{t-}-V_{B}^{t-}\right)\cdot Q_{A}^{t-}+Q_{B}^{t+}\cdot\alpha\cdot1+Q_{B}^{t+}\cdot1\\
= & V_{A}^{t-}\cdot Q_{A}^{t-}-V_{B}^{t-}\cdot Q_{B}^{t-}\cdot\alpha+Q_{B}^{t-}\cdot V_{B}^{t-}\cdot\alpha+Q_{B}^{t-}\cdot V_{B}^{t-}\\
= & V_{A}^{t-}\cdot Q_{A}^{t-}+V_{B}^{t-}\cdot Q_{B}^{t-}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note above used the fact 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{A}^{t-}=Q_{B}^{t-}\cdot\alpha$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Periodic
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When a given time period has passed from the last reset time, 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{A}^{t-}$
\end_inset

 grows to upper limit 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}_{A}$
\end_inset

, a periodic reset is triggered to restore the leverage ratio and net value
 of both classes.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{B}^{t-}$
\end_inset

 is less than 1, reset will be the same as the Contingent Downward reset.
 Otherwise, reset will be the same as Contingent Upward reset.
\end_layout

