\begin_layout Subsection
Premium and Discount
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Premium-and-Discount"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Like all fixed income products, Class A is expected to trade on premium
 or at discount with respect to its net value, depending on market condition.
 When Class A trades on premium, that generally indicates a higher demand
 for income over leverage and thus Class A buyers are getting lower yield.
 On the contrary, when Class A trades at discount, that implies a higher
 demand for leverage over income and thus Class A buyers are paying less
 and getting higher yield.
 In an orderly market, Class A's market price can be used to derive the
 current market cost of funding.
 As net values draws closer to resets, Class A might trade closer to its
 net value as trader start exploiting arbitrage opportunities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Arbitrage and Market Equilibrium
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The dual class tokens are two-way fungible to the underlying token (i.e.
 ETH).
 Thus, a price parity shall hold as below:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\alpha\cdot P_{A}^{t}+P_{B}^{t}=\alpha\cdot V_{A}^{t}+V_{B}^{t}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where, 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{A}^{t}$
\end_inset

 is the current price of Class A in USD,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $P_{B}^{t}$
\end_inset

 is the current price of Class B in USD.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Along with equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:creation"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:redemption"

\end_inset

 in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Creation-and-Redemption"

\end_inset

, below should hold:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{P_{t}}{P_{0}}\cdot\left(1-c\right)\leq\frac{\alpha\cdot P_{A}^{t}+P_{B}^{t}}{1+\alpha}\leq\frac{P_{t}}{P_{0}}\cdot\frac{1}{1-c}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On open market, arbitrage opportunity exists when Class A and Class B tokens
 trade away from their net values and above equation is violated on either
 side.
\end_layout

