\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Base Rate Discovery
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Arbitrary rate can be used for Class A coupon and it will be traded on premium
 or at discount based on the market required rate of return.
 However, it is desirable that Class A trades close to its net value, which
 means the coupon rate for Class A should be chosen close to the market
 rate.
 Currently there are few observable proxies in the market.
 Several centralized exchanges allowing margin trading are charging USD
 borrow rates in the range of 20% to 40% per annum.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As discussed in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Premium-and-Discount"

\end_inset

, the market premium or discount of Class A token may imply USD's borrow
 rate in this market.
 As the structure gain attractions, its implied rate could serve as an indicatio
n for other USD borrow practice in crypto market.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Optimal Reset Threshold and Frequency
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is important to keep leverage for Class B within certain range: not too
 high so as to protect Class A holders from sudden price drop and not too
 low so as to keep Class B attractive to leveraged investors.
 However, it is undesirable that resets, especially downward resets, happen
 too frequent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are two main parameters to be determined, the ratio between Class
 A and Class B shares, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

; and the lower limit of Class B net value, 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

, that triggers downward resets.
 The Chinese market over the years has concluded a broadly accepted set
 of parameters: 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is set to 1, meaning the quantities of Class A versus Class B is 1:1; 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 being 0.25, meaning a downward reset will be triggered if the underlying
 price dropped approximately 37% from last reset.
 This setup has been tested in extreme market events such as the mid-2015
 market crash and the early-2016 circuit breaker turmoil, where the reset
 clauses were all successfully implemented and protected the interests of
 Class A holders.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We observed that cryptocurrencies have considerably higher volatility than
 stock market indices.
 A series of back testings and Monte Carlo simulations will be performed
 to investigate the optimal parameters for dual class token structures.
 
\end_layout

